\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  Enumeration (Enum) in C#
\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  
\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  
\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  IEnumerable,ICollection,IList
\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  
\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  IEnumerable - Basic interface for iteration over collection,allows the use of foreach to iterate over the collection
\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  ICollection - Implements IEnumerable, Adit\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 onal features to add/remove items to the list of items/objects
\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  IList \tab \tab  - Implements ICollection,Aditonal features to Add/Remove items at a specifc index to the list of items.objects\tab 
\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506  IQueryable  - IQueryable inherits from IEnumerable, so anything you can do with IEnumerable, you can do with IQueryable too. 
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 The key difference is where the query is executed:
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 With IEnumerable, the query is executed in-memory (on the client). Even if it\hich\f31506 \rquote \loch\f31506 s connected to a database (like Entity Framework), 
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 it fet\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 ches all the data first, and then applies filters in memory.
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 With IQueryable, the query is translated into SQL and executed on the server/database, 
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 so only the filtered data is retrieved, making it much more efficient for large datasets.
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab 
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 // Assume dbContext.Users is a DbSet<User>
\par 
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 // IEnumerable: Fetches all users into memory, then filters
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 IEnumerable<User> usersEnum = dbContext.Users;
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 var filteredEnum = usersEnum.Where(u => u.Name == "John");
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab 
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 // IQueryable: Translates to SQL WHERE clause and filters in DB
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 IQueryable<User> usersQuery = dbContext.Users;
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 var filteredQuery = usersQuery.Where(u => u.Name == "John");
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 filteredEnum causes all users to be loaded into memory, then filtered.
\par 
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 filteredQuery sends a SQL like SELECT * FROM Users WHERE Name = 'John'.\tab 
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab 
\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 LINQ queries are often lazily evaluated.
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 List<int> numbers = new List<int> \{ 1, 2, 3, 4, 5 \};
\par 
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 // LINQ query - not executed yet (deferred)
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 var evenNumbers = numbers.Where(n => n % 2 == 0);
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab 
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 //Modify the source AFTER query is defined
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 numbers.Add(7);
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab 
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 // Now execute the query
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 foreach (var num in evenNumbers)
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab 
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 Console.WriteLine(num);
\par \tab \tab \tab \tab \tab 
\par \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 Here 7 is not printed in the foreach because of c# lazy   evalution,
\par \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 because the query was not run until the foreach loop.
\par 
