\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 2. What areasync/await**, and how do they improve performance?
\par \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 Asynchronous programming allows a program to start a long-running task and continue executing other tasks without waiting for the first one to finish. 
\par \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 It keeps the application responsive and is especially useful for operations like file I/O and web requests.
\par \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 async is a keyword used to mark a method as asynchronous, meaning it can run o\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 perations without blocking the calling thread.
\par \tab \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 await is a keyword used inside an async method to pause execution until a Task completes, without blocking the thread.
\par \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 3. What is the difference betweenIEnumerable, IQueryable, ICollection**?
\par \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 IEnumerable is used to iterate over in-memory collections and executes LINQ queries in memory.
\par \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 IQueryable extends IEnumerable and is used for querying databases or remote data sources, executing queries on the server.
\par \tab \hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 ICollection also extends IEnumerable but allows mo\hich\af31506\dbch\af31505\loch\f31506 difying the collection with Add, Remove, and Count
